FINANCIAL STATEMENTS
Trading Account
• A trading account is a financial statement prepared by a
business to determine the gross profit or loss made from
the sale of stock. Stock here refers to goods bought for
resale.
If the sales revenue is greater than the cost of goods sold,
the difference is gross profit, but if the cost of goods sold is
greater than the sales revenue the difference is gross loss.
• some Importance of a Trading Account include
Specific Objectives
By the end of the topic, the teacher should be able to guide the
learner to -
a) Identify the various financial statements
b) explain the importance of each of the financial statements
c) explain the concept of trading period
d) prepare simple financial statements
e) explain the various types of capital
f) calculate the basic ratios from financial statements
g) explain the importance of each of the basic financial ratios
- the business is able to determine the cost of goods sold.
- the business is able to compare its performance over the
years.
Profit and Loss Account
• This is a financial statement that shows the overall
profitability of a business by comparing all the revenues
earned with the expenses incurred in a specific trading
period,
a) Financial Statements
The teacher should guide the learner in explaining the meaning of
financial statements and guide in identifying the basic financial
statements. Financial statements are the final accounts which
show the performance of a business at a given period of time.
These are:
• Trading accounts
• Profit and loss account
• Balance sheet
If the revenue is more than expenses, the difference is Net
Profit and if the expenses are more than the revenue
generated, then the difference is Net Loss.
Some of the importance of profit and loss account include:
It helps the business owner to assess the expenses incurred
in operating a business in a given period.
Helps the business to determine its net profit or
net loss
Can be used by the government for taxation
purposes.
b) Trading Period
The teacher should guide the learner in explaining the meaning of
the concept "trading period". It refers to a time frame in which a
business undertakes its trading activities. The period usually
covers 12 months, though it can cover a shorter period
depending on the demand of the business. The trading period is
used to evaluate the performance of the business through
preparation of financial statements. The trading period is also
known as accounting period or financial year.
• The Balance Sheet
It is a financial statement showing the financial
position of a business at a particular date.
It displays the value of the assets, Liabilities
and capital of a business at a particular date.
